//3Sum
//Given an integer array nums, return all the triplets [nums[i], nums[j], nums[k]] such that i != j, i != k, and j != k, and nums[i] + nums[j] + nums[k] == 0.
//Notice that the solution set must not contain duplicate triplets.
//Example 1:
//Input: nums = [-1,0,1,2,-1,-4]
//Output: [[-1,-1,2],[-1,0,1]]
//Explanation: 
//nums[0] + nums[1] + nums[2] = (-1) + 0 + 1 = 0.
//nums[1] + nums[2] + nums[4] = 0 + 1 + (-1) = 0.
//nums[0] + nums[3] + nums[4] = (-1) + 2 + (-1) = 0.
//The distinct triplets are [-1,0,1] and [-1,-1,2].
//Notice that the order of the output and the order of the triplets does not matter.

Optimal Approach -> (Sorting + Two Pointers)

class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> threeSum(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<vector<int>> result;
        sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            if(i > 0 && nums[i] == nums[i - 1]) {
                continue;
            }
            int left = i + 1;
            int right = nums.size() - 1;
            while(left < right) {
                int sum = nums[i] + nums[left] + nums[right];
                if(sum < 0) {
                    left++;
                }
                else if(sum > 0) {
                    right--;
                }
                else {
                    result.push_back(
                        {nums[i], nums[left], nums[right]}
                    );
                    left++;
                    right--;
                    while(left < right &&
                          nums[left] == nums[left - 1]) {
                        left++;
                    }
                    while(left < right &&
                          nums[right] == nums[right + 1]) {
                        right--;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
};

Intuition ->
First sort the array.
For every element: nums[i] fix it as the first element of the triplet.
Now we need: nums[left] + nums[right] = -nums[i]
This becomes a Two Sum problem on a sorted array.
Use:
left = i + 1
right = n - 1
and move pointers according to the current sum.
Skip duplicates to avoid repeated triplets.

Complexity Analysis ->
Time Complexity -> O(n²)
where:
n = size of nums
Reason:
Sorting: O(n log n)
Outer loop: O(n)
Two pointers for each i: O(n)
Total: O(n²)

Space Complexity -> O(1)
Ignoring output array.
Reason:
Only pointer variables are used.

